The '''[[1976–77 NHL season|1976–77]] [[Cleveland Barons (NHL)|Cleveland Barons]] season''' was the first [[Season (sports)|season]] for this franchise in [[Cleveland]], after nine seasons in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] as the [[California Golden Seals|Oakland Seals/California Golden Seals]]. The Barons displaced the [[World Hockey Association]]'s [[Cleveland Crusaders]], who elected to relocate to Minnesota and become the [[Minnesota Fighting Saints]].
The Barons played in the tough [[Adams Division]] and spent most of the season in last place. Midway through the season, majority owner [[Melvin Swig]] announced the team might have trouble finishing the season. The club missed payroll twice in February, and only a loan from the league and [[National Hockey League Players' Association|NHLPA]] kept the team afloat. Following the season, minority owner George Gund III purchased a controlling interest in the club.<ref>http://www.sportsecyclopedia.com/nhl/cleveland/barons.html</ref>
==Offseason==
===Amateur Draft=== {{main article|1976 NHL Amateur Draft}}
The franchise participated in the 1976 Amateur Draft as the California Golden Seals, the move to Cleveland not being approved until mid-July.
