The '''Monster Bat Incident 1771''' concerns an attempt to use a [[cricket bat|bat]] that was as wide as the [[wicket]], during a cricket match between [[Chertsey Cricket Club|Chertsey]] and [[Hambledon Club|Hambledon]] at [[Laleham Burway]] that lasted from 23 September to 24 September 1771. Controversy arose when Chertsey's [[Thomas White (cricketer, born c. 1740)|Thomas White]] attempted to use the bat, while the Hambledon players objected. Ultimately Hambledon won the match by one run.<ref>''Fresh Light on 18th Century Cricket'' by [[G B Buckley]]</ref> The incident is occasionally ascribed to [[Shock White|"Shock" White]],<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/wcm/content/story/235391.html Grim prophecy fulfilled: Wisden, March 1981]</ref> a contemporary of Thomas White, but they were different players.
Afterwards, a formal protest was written by [[Thomas Brett (cricketer)|Thomas Brett]] and signed by himself, [[Richard Nyren]] and [[John Small (cricketer)|John Small]]. The incident brought about a change in the [[Laws of cricket]], as confirmed in 1774, whereby the maximum width of the bat was set at four and one quarter inches. This ruling has remained intact.
